## Questions

- [Is there public support for reducing income differences in Ireland?]{.big}  
  - Who supports ?  
  - Who should benefit ?  
  - Can support change over time? 


# Literature {.inverted}


## Societal level influences 

- Higher support for redistribution in countries with higher inequality [@velev_economic_2024; @finseraas_income_2009]  

- Support for redistribution remained apparently stable over time [@lupu_unequal_2023] and could be related to lack of major political reaction to income inequality.  

- @van_oorschot_social_2017 note that support for welfare policies, social transfers and redistribution is conditional on the social legitimacy of these policies' target groups  


## Socio-demographic predictors 

- Women are more progressive in relation to policy preferences and support for redistribution [@shorrocks_attitudinal_2020; @inglehart_cultural_2018; @grasso_are_2025]  

-  @steele_wealth_2022 find that older respondents are more favourable of income redistribution.  

- @grasso_are_2025 highlights the association between gender and generation, with the cohorts of women born after 1946 being more supportive of redistribution compared to men in their cohorts  


# Methods {.inverted}

## Data sources {.center}


::: {.columns}

::: {.column width = "70%"}

- **European Social Survey (2002 - 2024)**  
- European Election Studies - Voter Survey  
- Eurobarometer  
- National Election and Democracy Study   

:::

::: {.column width = "30%"}
![](./img/illu_ess.jpg)

:::

:::


# Key findings {.inverted}

## Support for government action

**3 in 4** Irish residents agree that the *government should reduce differences in income*.

![](./img/fig_c2_eumap.svg){fig-align="center" width="75%"} 


::: {.aside}
Source: European Social Survey
:::




## Agreement by sex, Ireland 2002–2024

::: {.columns}

::: {.column width="30%"}

Considering all 11 rounds of the ESS together, there is a significantly
higher support for redistribution among female respondents compared to male
respondents.

:::

::: {.column width="70%"}
![](./img/fig_c2_sex.svg){fig-align="center"} 

:::

:::

::: {.aside}
Source: European Social Survey
:::

## Agreement by SES, Ireland 2002-2024

::: {.columns}

::: {.column width="40%"}

The analysis by social class, household income, or "financial situation" show a negative relationship between SES and support for redistribution. But remains over 60% in all groups.
:::

::: {.column width="60%"}
![](./img/fig_c2_class.svg){fig-align="center"} 

:::

:::


::: {.aside}
Source: European Social Survey
:::


## Other positive associations{.center}

- Born in Ireland  
- Younger
- Left of the political scale  


# Welfare for whom? {.inverted}
Perceptions of deservingness and beliefs about the role of social supports


## Who should receive higher priority from the government

::: {.columns}

::: {.column width="30%" .smaller}
...higher agreement for gov. support for working parents and older citizens.

...lower agreement for govt supports for the unemployed
:::

::: {.column width="70%"}

![](./img/fig_c3_deservingness.svg){fig-align="center" width="80%"} 
:::

:::

::: {.aside}
Source: European Social Survey
:::


## Beliefs about social benefits, Ireland

![](./img/fig_c3_benefits_present.svg){fig-align="center" width="75%"} 

::: {.aside}
Source: European Social Survey
:::

## Perceptions on fairness

> Please think about the top 10% of employees working full-time in Ireland, earning more than €81,000 per year. In your opinion, are these incomes unfairly low, fair, or unfairly high? Please think generally about people earning this level of incomes

> And now please think about the bottom 10% of employees working full-time in Ireland, earning less than €19,000 per year.


## Support for redistribution and perceived fairness of the incomes

![](./img/fig_c3_fairness_present_none.svg){fig-align="center" width="90%"} 

::: {.aside}
Source: European Social Survey
:::

## Support for redistribution and perceived fairness of the incomes

![](./img/fig_c3_fairness_present_no.svg){fig-align="center" width="90%"} 

::: {.aside}
Source: European Social Survey
:::

## Support for redistribution and perceived fairness of the incomes

![](./img/fig_c3_fairness_present_pl.svg){fig-align="center" width="90%"} 

::: {.aside}
Source: European Social Survey
:::


## Support for redistribution and perceived fairness of the incomes

![](./img/fig_c3_fairness_present_ie.svg){fig-align="center" width="90%"} 

::: {.aside}
Source: European Social Survey
:::

## Support for redistribution and perceived fairness of the incomes

![](./img/fig_c3_fairness_present_all.svg){fig-align="center" width="90%"} 

::: {.aside}
Source: European Social Survey
:::

## Attitudes to taxation in Ireland 

<br>

- 34% of Irish residents indicate that they *agree with higher taxes if it means more or better public services*. This is the 6th highest percentage across 27 EU countries. 

- 35% believe taxes are too high, another 25% think they should remain at their current level.

::: {.aside}
Source: Eurobarometer Flash Survey 2025.
:::

# Change over time {.inverted}

## Support for government action reducing differences in income

![](./img/fig_c4_eutime.svg){fig-align="center" width="80%"} 

::: {.aside}
Source: European Social Survey
:::

## COVID-19, Ireland 2021-2022

::: {.columns}

::: {.column width="40%"}

Those who experienced job loss during the COVID-19 pandemic are more supportive of redistribution, regardless of their financial situation or social class.
:::

::: {.column width="60%"}
![](./img/fig_c4_covid.svg){fig-align="center"}
:::
:::

::: {.aside}
Source: European Social Survey.
:::

## Irish Government campaign


![](./img/dsp_bus.jpg)

:::{.aside}
Image: [Thecreed.ie/dsp-welfare-3-2](https://thecreed.ie/dsp-welfare-cheats-blog)
:::

## Irish Government campaign

::: {.columns}

::: {.column width="40%"}

... seven-day exponential moving average of three variables in the 30-day time window around the launch of the campaign on 17 April 2017.

:::

::: {.column width="60%"}
![](./img/fig_c4_dsp_mean.svg){fig-align="center" width="70%"}
:::

:::

::: {.aside}
Source: European Social Survey
:::

## Irish Government campaign

::: {.columns}

::: {.column width="40%"}

Statistically significant decrease on the level of agreement that '*social benefits prevents poverty*' among interviews conducted after the launch of the campaign compared to those interviewed before the launch.

:::

::: {.column width="60%"}
![](./img/fig_c4_dsp_model.svg){fig-align="center" width="100%"}
:::

:::

::: {.aside}
Source: European Social Survey
:::

## Conclusions and policy implications

- Strong support for Irish government to reduce income differences, especially to address “unfairly low income” of those in the bottom income decile. 

- Support for redistribution higher among low-income households, females, younger people. 

- Higher than EU-average level of support for higher taxes conditional of providing better public services (may be motivated by self-interest but also related to support for redistribution)  

## Conclusions and policy implications

- Pandemic, which saw a huge increase in government supports, was associated with an increase in support for redistribution, especially among those directly effected  

- Negative stereotypes about welfare recipients may undermine this support

- Importance of communication of the role of social protection in addressing risks and the rights/entitlements of citizens  


